1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,650
Consider which producers make the money from movies.

2
00:00:03,920 --> 00:00:07,331
The get-rich-quick producer proceeds to make a picture.

3
00:00:07,440 --> 00:00:12,610
Putting money ahead of entertainment, service, he cuts corners everywhere.

4
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:18,050
He buys a poorly written script and employs second-rate writers to adapt it.

5
00:00:18,240 --> 00:00:24,291
In employing actors, arranging sets, even recording sound, he puts money first.

6
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:30,291
This producer thinks the moviegoer is a sucker, someone who can't tell good from bad.

7
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:35,010
But the get-rich-quick producer seldom does get rich quick.

8
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:43,411
There never is a bandwagon movement to buy anything second-class, especially when it is given a first-class price.

9
00:00:43,840 --> 00:00:49,570
The producer who enjoys the largest profits from pictures puts entertainment ahead of money.

10
00:00:49,840 --> 00:00:57,570
Rather than chisel the moviegoer, he does everything possible to give people more and better entertainment than they expect to get.

11
00:00:57,840 --> 00:00:58,771
The result?

12
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:05,010
People like the movie, it gets talked about, it gets good reviews, and it makes money.

13
00:01:05,679 --> 00:01:10,530
Again, put service first, and money takes care of itself.

14
00:01:11,440 --> 00:01:17,251
The waitress, who concentrates on giving the best possible service, needn't worry about tips.

15
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:18,291
They'll be there.

16
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:23,251
But her counterpart, who overlooks the empty coffee cups, why refill them?

17
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:27,251
They don't look like tippers, won't find any gratuities.

18
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:32,771
The secretary, who resolves to make those letters look better than the boss expects,

19
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:35,171
will do all right on future paychecks.

20
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:39,331
But the secretary who thinks, why worry about a few smudges?

21
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:42,291
What do they expect for $65 a week?

22
00:01:42,480 --> 00:01:45,570
She is stuck at $65 a week.

23
00:01:46,161 --> 00:01:52,291
The salesman who gives full service to an account need harbor no fears he'll lose the account.

24
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:59,411
Here is a simple but powerful rule that will help you to develop the put-service-first attitude.

25
00:01:59,760 --> 00:02:03,090
Always give people more than they expect to get.

26
00:02:03,440 --> 00:02:07,570
Each little extra something you do for others is a money seed.

27
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:13,171
Volunteering to work late and get the department out of a tight spot is a money seed.

28
00:02:13,280 --> 00:02:18,610
Giving customers extra service is a money seed because it brings customers back.

29
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:23,251
Advancing a new idea that will increase efficiency is a money seed.

30
00:02:23,601 --> 00:02:29,171
Money seeds, of course, grow money, plant service, and harvest money.

31
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:33,090
Spend some time each day answering this question.

32
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:36,291
How can I give more than is expected of me?

33
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:38,130
Then apply the answers.

34
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:42,130
Put service first, and money takes care of itself.

